TITLE: Saudi activist sentenced to 34 years in prison for Twitter activity
SUMMARY: Saudi women's rights campaigner Salma al-Shehab was sentenced to 34 years in prison on Monday for her activity on Twitter, according to court documents viewed by CNN.

TITLE: After Wyoming defeat, Cheney prepares for the longer-term fight against Trump -- and her own political future
SUMMARY: The day after losing the Republican primary for Wyoming's House seat, Rep. Liz Cheney is positioning herself for a longer-term fight with former President Donald Trump.

TITLE: Biden 'rejects' defunding the FBI amid calls from some Republicans
SUMMARY: The White House is strongly condemning calls from some members of the Republican Party, including some elected lawmakers, to "defund the FBI" in the wake of last week's search of former President Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago estate.

TITLE: Opinion: The IRS is getting a big financial boost. Republicans are not happy about it
SUMMARY: Republicans have been railing against the Inflation Reduction Act, and there's one provision they really dislike: The plan to bolster the beleaguered Internal Revenue Service. Investigative journalist Casey Michel writes that the GOP has been trying for years to starve the IRS of revenue and resources, but the bill will inject $80 billion into the agency.

TITLE: DeSantis' proposed new rules for pension investments push Florida into fight against Wall Street
SUMMARY: As soon as next week, Florida pension fund managers could be barred from considering the social impact of their financial decisions as Gov. Ron DeSantis opens a new front in his anti-"woke" crusade, this time focused on Wall Street and corporate CEOs.

TITLE: Family of US Navy officer jailed in Japan over fatal car crash calls on Biden to intervene
SUMMARY: The family of a US Navy officer imprisoned in Japan rallied outside the White House on Wednesday to protest his detention and try to attract President Joe Biden's attention to the case.

TITLE: Christianity Fast Facts
SUMMARY: View CNN's Fast Facts to learn more about the most practiced religion in the world, Christianity.

TITLE: Labor Day Fast Facts
SUMMARY: Read CNN's Fast Facts about Labor Day, a legal holiday celebrated in the United States and Puerto Rico to honor working people.

TITLE: Opinion: What Liz Cheney should do next
SUMMARY: The President should appoint Liz Cheney as a cabinet-level czar on election integrity and the preservation of democracy once her term is up in January, write Arick Wierson and Bradley Honan.

TITLE: Tiny glowing fish is full of antifreeze to help it survive Greenland's icy waters
SUMMARY: Tiny glowing fish that live in icy waters off the coast of Greenland are full of naturally occurring antifreeze proteins that help them survive in subzero waters, according to new research. But time may be running out for the snailfish as the Arctic warms.

TITLE: Workers file for union vote at another Amazon facility
SUMMARY: The union that was the first to win a representation vote at an Amazon facility has filed for an election among about 400 employees at another Amazon distribution center.

TITLE: A$AP Rocky pleads not guilty to assault charges
SUMMARY: The rapper was charged with two counts of assault with a semiautomatic firearm

TITLE: Target profit plunges 90% as inflation-weary shoppers pull back
SUMMARY: Target reported profit plunged 90% in the second quarter, falling far short of expectations, as inflation-weary customers pulled back on spending on nonessential items.

TITLE: Bob Newhart Fast Facts
SUMMARY: Read CNN's Fast Facts on Bob Newhart and learn more about the life of the comedian, actor and writer.

TITLE: The 9 p.m. cable news hour is primed for reinvention
SUMMARY: Is there an opening for reinvention, or at least modernization, of the cable news formula? If so, the opportunity is at 9 o'clock Eastern.

TITLE: Kanye West's Yeezy Gap clothes are being displayed in giant trash bags
SUMMARY: Ye has come under fire for what's being described as a visual merchandising strategy at the Gap.

TITLE: Explosion erupts inside Kabul mosque, police say
SUMMARY: An explosion erupted inside a mosque during evening prayers in Kabul, Afghanistan on Wednesday, killing at least three people and injuring dozens of others.

TITLE: How Liz Cheney lost Wyoming's lone seat in the House
SUMMARY: Rep. Liz Cheney's supporters say her reelection hopes were doomed on January 13, 2021, when a week after the insurrection at the Capitol, she and nine other House Republicans voted to impeach former President Donald Trump.

TITLE: Spacewalk cut short by issue with Russian cosmonaut's spacesuit: 'Drop everything and start going back right away'
SUMMARY: A Russian cosmonaut was repeatedly ordered to drop what he was working on and return to the International Space Station's airlock because of an issue with his spacesuit. The spacewalk was cut short.

TITLE: Ukraine admits it was behind three explosions in Crimea. Here's what we know
SUMMARY: Ukraine was behind three explosions that rocked the Russian-annexed province of Crimea this past week, including an explosion at a Russian air base in Crimea's west coast on Tuesday that wrecked several airplanes, according to a Ukrainian government report circulated internally and shared with CNN by a â€‹Ukrainian official.

TITLE: Amazon workers walk off job at air freight facility to call for better pay and working conditions
SUMMARY: A coalition of Amazon employees walked off the job on Monday at an air freight facility in San Bernardino, California, demanding better pay and working conditions, in the latest sign that worker organizing efforts continue to spread across the tech giant's vast retail and logistics network.

TITLE: 'Irate parent' is arrested in Georgia for discharging pepper spray on school bus
SUMMARY: An "irate parent" was arrested after she boarded a Georgia school bus and discharged a can of pepper spray -- exposing two dozen students onboard, according to the Glynn County Schools.

TITLE: Monkeypox case reported in man whose 'primary risk factor' was close, nonsexual contact at a crowded outdoor event
SUMMARY: Most monkeypox cases in the current outbreak have been linked to sexual activity, but research published Wednesday by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention offers new insight into other ways it may be spreading.

TITLE: Electric vehicle credits just completely changed. Here's what it means for car buyers
SUMMARY: The newly signed Inflation Reduction Act will have big implications for electric vehicle buyers. Some popular electric vehicles may become eligible for a tax credit once again, while other cars that were eligible this month will not be for the foreseeable future. Here's what you need to know as a consumer.

TITLE: Why you need to stop adding salt and what you can do to make your food taste good instead
SUMMARY: Adding that sprinkle of salt may help make your meal feel complete, but it could be adding to your risk for premature death, according to a new study. Experts explain how to cut back on salt while still enjoying the foods you love.

TITLE: 911 call reveals neighbors' panic after Anne Heche crashed into an occupied home in LA
SUMMARY: While questions remain about that tragic day, more information has come to light about events leading up to Heche's crash and audio from a 911 call reveals how witnesses tried to help.

TITLE: CDC announces sweeping reorganization, aimed at changing the agency's culture and restoring public trust
SUMMARY: Big changes are coming to the United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which recently celebrated its 75th anniversary as the nation's lead public health agency.

TITLE: More than half of GOP governor nominees have questioned or denied the legitimacy of the 2020 election
SUMMARY: The Republican nominee in at least 21 of this year's 36 gubernatorial races is someone who has rejected, declined to affirm, raised doubts about, or tried to overturn Joe Biden's victory in the 2020 election.

TITLE: At least 11 Republican nominees for state elections chief have disputed the legitimacy of the 2020 election
SUMMARY: In at least 11 states, the Republican nominee for the job of overseeing future elections is someone who has questioned, rejected or tried to overturn the results of the 2020 election.

TITLE: Mike Pence says he'd consider testifying before January 6 committee if invited
SUMMARY: Former Vice President Mike Pence said Wednesday he would give "due consideration" to any formal invitation to testify before the House select committee investigating the January 6, 2021, attack on the US Capitol, while hinting at potential executive privilege issues.
